Fun and Easy TCO data¶

This short slide deck illustrates how well structured data combined with an intake catalog can be easy to browse and explore. Topics can be explored in more depth by clicking down, or a new topic can be opened by clicking right.

Opening the catalog¶

The Tropical Cloud Observations Group of the Max Planck Institute for Meteorology decided to serve all of its data using zarr over html. The data is compiled (or is being compiled) as a single data set, using intake and the catalog:

"http://tcodata.mpimet.mpg.de/catalog.yaml"

Presently only a few instruments have been added, more or on their way.

Below we give some examples showing how to navigate through the catalog. Next we give some examples using the data files that we identified by browsing.

In [1]:
import intake
cat = intake.open_catalog("http://tcodata.mpimet.mpg.de/catalog.yaml")

Inspecting the radar data¶

First we look at a time-slice of the radar date, randomly picking a 2 day period in early March of 2023. Then we zoom in on an interesting echo.

In [5]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt # for making plots
import seaborn as sns # for making plots prettier

radar = cat.BCO.radar_MBRS_c1_v1.to_dask()
radar.sel(time=slice("2023-03-02","2023-03-03"),alt=slice(0,17000)).Ze.plot(x="time",cmap="turbo",figsize=(15,5))
sns.despine(offset = 10)

Combining instruments¶

While the radar makes it look like a long period of rain, most of the reflectivities near the surface would hardly be perceptible as such. Below we plot the near-surface reflectivities as a time-series along with some measurements with the weather station.

In [21]:
radar = cat.BCO.radar_MBRS_c1_v1.to_dask().sel(time=slice("2023-03-03T01","2023-03-03T03"))
wxt   = cat.BCO.surfacemet_wxt_v1.to_dask().sel(time=slice("2023-03-03T00","2023-03-03T03"))

fig, axs = plt.subplots(3,1, sharex=True, figsize = (10,3),constrained_layout=True)
axs[0].plot(wxt.time,wxt.T)
axs[1].plot(wxt.time,wxt.RI)

axs[2].set_ylim(0,30.)
axs[2].hlines(20.,xmin=radar.time[0],xmax=radar.time[-1],colors='grey',linestyles='solid',lw=0.5)

axs[0].set_ylabel('T / degC')

Synthesizing data with Joint Histograms¶

Here we show how easy it is to stride through the entire data set, nearly 4 million grid points for this record, to look at summary statistics, in this case reflectivity and doppler velocity histograms binned by height. The advantage of the notebook presentation is that it documents what was actually done, not what was intended to have been done. And it is reproducible.

We look over the entire record (from Dec 2022 to mid March 2023), nearly 4 million time stamps.

Making the histograms with seaborn¶

In [9]:
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
sns.set_context('notebook')

radar   = cat.BCO.radar_MBRS_c1_v1.to_dask()
ntimes  = len(radar.time)
alts    = radar.alt[500::-5].values  # only look at every fifth height bin to speed up processing

zbins   = np.linspace(-60,30,31)  # specify 30 bins between -60 and 30 dBz reflectivities
vbins   = np.linspace(-8,4,37)    # specify 36 bins between -8 and 4 m/s doppler velocities
zhist   = np.zeros((len(alts),len(zbins)-1))
vhist   = np.zeros((len(alts),len(vbins)-1))

for k,alt in enumerate(alts):
    zhist[k,:], edges = np.histogram(radar.Ze.sel(alt=alt) , bins=zbins, normed=None, weights=None, density=None)
    vhist[k,:], edges = np.histogram(radar.VEL.sel(alt=alt), bins=vbins, normed=None, weights=None, density=None)

zdf = pd.DataFrame(zhist, columns = np.round(zbins[1:]- np.diff(zbins)[0]/2,1), index=np.round(alts/1000.,1) )
vdf = pd.DataFrame(vhist, columns = np.round(vbins[1:]- np.diff(vbins)[0]/2,1), index=np.round(alts/1000.,1) )
In [10]:
zdf = pd.DataFrame(zhist, columns = np.round(zbins[1:]- np.diff(zbins)[0]/2,1), index=np.round(alts/1000.,1) )
vdf = pd.DataFrame(vhist, columns = np.round(vbins[1:]- np.diff(vbins)[0]/2,1), index=np.round(alts/1000.,1) )
nmin  = ntimes/3000.
nmax  = ntimes/30.

ax    = sns.heatmap(zdf, mask=zdf<nmin,linewidth = 0.5, vmax=nmax,cmap = 'turbo')#, xticklabels=edges, yticklabels=10)
ax.set_xlabel('$Z_\mathrm{e}$ / dBZ',)
ax.set_ylabel('height / m amsl')

That's it .. but maybe you noticed?¶

  • how lucky we were to stumble on the strong updraft feature ($V_\mathrm{Doppler}>6$m/s in early March).
  • how much reflectivity there is (Ze < 15dBz) that doesn't show up as rain
  • that we rarely get echos above 15 km, and ice clouds occurance maximizes closer to 12 km
  • how many Mielsinger-Bony clouds are in the Malkus-Albright layer

Thanks to the TCO Group for making the data fun and easy.
